The dual aims of this book are set forth in its opening paragraph as "(a) to examine the validity of a concept which is rarely stated explicitly but on which medical activities largely rest, namely that human health depends essentially on a mechanistic approach based on understanding of the structure and function of the body and of the disease processes that affect it; and (b) to consider the significance of the conclusions for medicine, particularly in relation to health services, medical education, and medical research."
The first part of the book thus addresses the determinants of health and the second, the role of medicine.
A disease classification is introduced which isfollowed in much of the subsequent discussion. One category includes diseases which are determined atfertilization and this isfurther divided into genetic diseases and "conditions associated with the genetically programmed wearing out of organs at the end of life." The second category comprises conditions which occur only in an appropriate environment. This class is subdivided according to the prenatal or postnatal effect of the environmental influences.
Mortality in England and Wales has decreased from over 20 deaths per 1,000 population in 1851 to fewer than 8 deaths per 1,000 in 1971. Almost three-quarters of the decrease in the period 1851-1971 is attributed to a fall in mortality from conditions associated with micro-organisms. The largest portion of this change (40 percent) was in mortality from airborne diseases, most conspicuously respiratory tuberculosis which accountedfor 17percent of the total decline. Twenty-one percent of the decrease was from waterborne and food-borne diseases, primarily cholera, diarrhea, and dysentery. The remaining decrease, 13 percent of the total, is accounted for among other diseases attributable to micro-organisms, such as those within the rubric convulsions and teething. Counter to
