Four causesfor the decline in mortalityfrom infectious diseases are advanced and assessed. These are: 1. changes in the character of the diseases, i.e., changes in the interaction between organism and host; 2. developments in immunization and therapy; 3. reduction of exposure to infection; and 4. improvements in nutrition. Examination of the probable effect of each of these indicates that the changes in mortality may be attributed primarily to improved nutrition. Reduced exposure to infection had some effect upon mortality during the nineteenth century, as did immunization and therapy in the twentieth. There is little evidence of general changes in the character of the infectious diseases during the period under study.
About one-quarter of the decrease in mortality in England and Wales between 1851 and 1971 was a result of changing death rates for non-infective conditions. Deaths from infanticide and starvation may have been decreasing during the nineteenth century, but most of the contribution to a more favorable mortality experience from non-infectious conditions occurred after 1900. This category of diseases is a heterogeneous one and has been subject to changes in terminology and classification. The conditions accounting for most of the mortality change within this group are those associated with prematurity and old age.
Identification of improvement in nutrition as the major causal factor in the decline in mortality is based upon the assumption of a large increase in food supplies after 1800 and the postulation of a nutritional improvement as a necessary condition for both the observed population growth and mortality decline. The decrease in mortality from water-borne andfood-borne diseases appears to be related to the various improvements in hygiene which occurred during the latter half of the nineteenth century.
A number of infectious diseases have been subject to notable advances in immunization and therapy. Their mortality was decreasing prior to the introduction of these medical advances which during this century had little observable impact upon the continuing downward trends. The conspicuous exceptions to this general conclusion are the developments of streptomycin therapy for tuberculosis and poliomyelitis vaccine.
