Certain residual health problems remain as mortality from infectious diseases has been reduced. These include the congential diseases and disabilities, psychiatric illness, and a group of other diseases which may be preventable. Progress toward their prevention and control is likely to be more dependent upon modification of behavioral and environmental influences than upon medical
interventions.

The second section of the book, on the role of medicine, begins with a discussion of the implications of the observations and conclusions from the first section for present-day health services. These findings suggest initiatives for public policy relating to nutrition, behavior, and the environment. In the provision of personal health services, the appraisal of the effectiveness of medical technology indicates a need to redress the balance between technology and care. It is essential that a more critical stance be adopted toward quality issues in health services and that adequate evaluations be conducted prior to the general introduction of new procedures.
The scope of medical education should be expanded to place increased emphasis upon the environmental and behavioral influences acting upon a nation's health and upon an expanded and integrated concept of personal care through all stages of illness. These changes may have some effect upon the selection of students entering upon medical training but their most important impact will be upon the medical curriculum. The student should be trained to understand better the origins of disease, the effectiveness of medical interventions and how they should be assessed, and the needs of the patient beyond the acute episode of illness. The medical school and its hospital must cease their current isolation from many of the major health problems; they must also expand their interests and services to expose students to the total range of illness, disability, and modalities of care.
